Source: The Age, Thu 7 Aug 2003 [edited]
<http://www.theage.com.au/articles/2003/08/07/1060145794843.html>

New Zealand: Suspected Case of New Variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease
--------------------------------------------------------------------
New Zealand may have its first case of new variant Creutzfeldt-Jakob
disease [abbreviated as CJD (new var. or vCJD in ProMED-mail], government
officials said. The Health Ministry is expected to announce the case [see
part (2) below], after a CJD patient's progress failed to follow a normal
pattern. New Zealand gets about 3 or 4 normal [i.e. sproadic] CJD cases
annually, but has been waiting for the first case to occur among New
Zealanders who ate beef in Britain when infected meat was still being sold
there. The normal form of the disease can take between 10 and 30 years to
incubate in humans.
New Zealand's agricultural industry was gearing up to fend off any impact
the case might have on consumer perceptions of New Zealand meat. A
spokeswoman for the Minister of Agriculture and Forestry said that the
matter was a human health issue --- there was no mad cow disease, bovine
spongiform encephalopathy (BSE), in the national cattle herd. She said some
confusion had been sown by a incorrect British report that New Zealand was
about to report a foot and mouth disease outbreak. That rumour was also
wrong, but financial commentators said the speculation had left currency
markets "very nervous".
A medical expert had said a case of CJD in a New Zealander was "presenting
very unusually" and authorities had sent away [material for testing] which
would take one or two weeks to give a definitive result, a spokeswoman for
Agriculture Minister Jim Sutton said. "But there's no evidence of BSE in
our cattle herd," she said. Major concerns for health officials are
expected to be tracing the suspect case, and checking whether the patient
has donated blood.
[Sporadic CJD] occurs in about one in 1 million people annually. A gene
mutation that runs in families [accounts for] 5 per cent to 10 per cent of
cases of CJD. CJD, which is incurable and always fatal, can also be passed
on by tissue transplants and, in theory, in blood, but nearly 200 people,
mostly in Britain and other parts of Europe, [are presumed to have
contracted] the new variant form, vCJD from eating infected beef products
[but this has not been confirmed unequivocally. - Mod.CP].
